          "title": "The testament — Peter's imminent exodus (1:12-15)",
          "body": "Verses 12-15 explain why Peter is writing now. He knows his death is *imminent* (*tachinē* — swift, soon), and *the Lord Jesus Christ has made clear to me* — almost certainly an allusion to John 21:18-19, where the risen Christ foretold Peter's martyrdom by stretched-out hands. Peter calls his body an *earthly dwelling* (*skenoma* — tent, the temporary lodging Paul also uses in 2 Corinthians 5:1-4) and his death an *exodos* (departure) — the same word Luke uses of Jesus' coming death in Luke 9:31, where Moses and Elijah on the Transfiguration mount discussed His *exodus* with Him. The verbal echo is not accidental. Peter, who witnessed that conversation, casts his own death in the same vocabulary. His apostolic concern is testamentary: *I will also be diligent that at any time after my departure you will be able to call these things to mind.* This letter exists so that the church will have a permanent reminder when the eyewitness is gone."
